"Heijs S.K., Aloisi G., Bouloubassi I., Pancost R.D., Pierre C., Sinninghe Damsté J.S., Gottschal J.C., Van Elsas J.D., Forney L.J.","Microbial community structure in three deep-sea carbonate crusts",2006,"Microbial Ecology","52","3",,"451","462",,,10.1007/s00248-006-9099-8,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-33845412481&partnerID=40&md5=3eba3a8597671a403e3edf728ab9ff57","Department of Microbiology, Center of Ecological and Evolutionary Studies, University of Groningen, P.O. Box 14, 9750 AA Haren, Netherlands; Laboratoire d'Océanographie Dynamique et de Climatologie, Université Pierre et Marie Curie, 4, place Jussieu, 75252 Paris, France; Laboratoire de Physique et Chimie Marines, Université Pierre et Marie Curie, 4, Place Jussieu, 75252 Paris, France; Department of Marine Biogeochemistry and Toxicology, Netherlands Institute for Sea Research, P.O. Box 59, 1790AB Den Burg (Texel), Netherlands; UMR 5125-PEPS-CNRS-UCBL, Bâtiment GEODE, Domaine Sci. Doua, 2 Rue Dubois, F-69622 Villeurbanne Cedex, France; Organic Geochemistry Unit, School of Chemistry, University of Bristol, Bristol BS8 1TS, United Kingdom; Department of Biological Sciences, University of Idaho, Moscow, ID 83844-3051, United States","Heijs, S.K., Department of Microbiology, Center of Ecological and Evolutionary Studies, University of Groningen, P.O. Box 14, 9750 AA Haren, Netherlands; Aloisi, G., Laboratoire d'Océanographie Dynamique et de Climatologie, Université Pierre et Marie Curie, 4, place Jussieu, 75252 Paris, France, UMR 5125-PEPS-CNRS-UCBL, Bâtiment GEODE, Domaine Sci. Doua, 2 Rue Dubois, F-69622 Villeurbanne Cedex, France; Bouloubassi, I., Laboratoire de Physique et Chimie Marines, Université Pierre et Marie Curie, 4, Place Jussieu, 75252 Paris, France; Pancost, R.D., Department of Marine Biogeochemistry and Toxicology, Netherlands Institute for Sea Research, P.O. Box 59, 1790AB Den Burg (Texel), Netherlands, Organic Geochemistry Unit, School of Chemistry, University of Bristol, Bristol BS8 1TS, United Kingdom; Pierre, C., Laboratoire d'Océanographie Dynamique et de Climatologie, Université Pierre et Marie Curie, 4, place Jussieu, 75252 Paris, France; Sinninghe Damsté, J.S., Department of Marine Biogeochemistry and Toxicology, Netherlands Institute for Sea Research, P.O. Box 59, 1790AB Den Burg (Texel), Netherlands; Gottschal, J.C., Department of Microbiology, Center of Ecological and Evolutionary Studies, University of Groningen, P.O. Box 14, 9750 AA Haren, Netherlands; Van Elsas, J.D., Department of Microbiology, Center of Ecological and Evolutionary Studies, University of Groningen, P.O. Box 14, 9750 AA Haren, Netherlands; Forney, L.J., Department of Microbiology, Center of Ecological and Evolutionary Studies, University of Groningen, P.O. Box 14, 9750 AA Haren, Netherlands, Department of Biological Sciences, University of Idaho, Moscow, ID 83844-3051, United States","Carbonate crusts in marine environments can act as sinks for carbon dioxide. Therefore, understanding carbonate crust formation could be important for understanding global warming. In the present study, the microbial communities of three carbonate crust samples from deep-sea mud volcanoes in the eastern Mediterranean were characterized by sequencing 16S ribosomal RNA (rRNA) genes amplified from DNA directly retrieved from the samples. In combination with the mineralogical composition of the crusts and lipid analyses, sequence data were used to assess the possible role of prokaryotes in crust formation. Collectively, the obtained data showed the presence of highly diverse communities, which were distinct in each of the carbonate crusts studied. Bacterial 16S rRNA gene sequences were found in all crusts and the majority was classified as α-, γ-, and δ- Proteobacteria. Interestingly, sequences of Proteobacteria related to Halomonas and Halovibrio sp., which can play an active role in carbonate mineral formation, were present in all crusts. Archaeal 16S rRNA gene sequences were retrieved from two of the crusts studied. Several of those were closely related to archaeal sequences of organisms that have previously been linked to the anaerobic oxidation of methane (AOM). However, the majority of archaeal sequences were not related to sequences of organisms known to be involved in AOM. In combination with the strongly negative δ 13C values of archaeal lipids, these results open the possibility that organisms with a role in AOM may be more diverse within the Archaea than previously suggested. Different communities found in the crusts could carry out similar processes that might play a role in carbonate crust formation. © 2006 Springer Science+Business Media, Inc.",,"bacterial DNA; carbon dioxide; carbonic acid derivative; lipid; methane; RNA 16S; sea water; bacterium; carbonate; community structure; DNA; genetic analysis; lipid; marine environment; microbial community; mud volcano; oceanic crust; prokaryote; RNA; anaerobic growth; Archaebacterium; article; biodiversity; chemistry; classification; genetics; greenhouse effect; metabolism; microbiology; phylogeny; Proteobacteria; sediment; volcano; Anaerobiosis; Archaea; Biodiversity; Carbon Dioxide; Carbonates; DNA, Bacterial; Geologic Sediments; Greenhouse Effect; Lipids; Methane; Phylogeny; Proteobacteria; RNA, Ribosomal, 16S; Seawater; Volcanic Eruption; Water Microbiology; Archaea; Bacteria (microorganisms); Deltaproteobacteria; Halomonas; Prokaryota; Proteobacteria",,"carbon dioxide, 124-38-9, 58561-67-4; lipid, 66455-18-3; methane, 74-82-8; Carbon Dioxide, 124-38-9; Carbonates; DNA, Bacterial; Lipids; Methane, 74-82-8; RNA, Ribosomal, 16S",,,,"Aharon, P., Carbon and oxygen isotope tracers of submarine hydrocarbon emissions: Northern Gulf of Mexico (1994) Israel J Earth Sci, 43, pp. 157-164; Aloisi, G., Pierre, C., Rouchy, J.M., Foucher, J.P., Woodside, J., Methane-related authigenic carbonates of eastern Mediterranean Sea mud volcanoes and their possible relation to gas hydrate destabilis